    <h1 class="header-title">Cyclone Definition</h1>

    <hr>

    <p>A cyclone is defined "as a system of winds rotating inwards to an area of low barometric pressure". <br> <br>

    In order for cyclones to form, it must be over <strong> sea surface temperatures of 26 degrees Celsius </strong>. The warm water causes
    the water to evaporate, and form clouds and if there is <strong> low atmospheric pressure</strong>, <br> the clouds are pulled in 
    and begin to rotate. Cyclone are generally known for their <strong> high wind speeds that exceed 63 km/h</strong>, even greater at <strong> its center with 90 km/h</strong>.
    Surprisingly, cyclones never originate on the equator <br> due to the Coriolis effect where Earth's rotational forces in that area are very weak.
    And will obviously target various sea basins across the globe such as the Pacific, Indian and Atlantic Oceans.
    
    <br> <br> A cyclone can be categorised by its nature and intensity, where nature refers
    to its title and intensity to its numerical rating; both mutually inclusive. Where the higher the cyclone's sustained wind speed, the higher <br>
    its nature and intensity:</p>

